Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': "--- a/ext/spl/spl_dllist.c\n+++ b/ext/spl/spl_dllist.c\n@@ -1023,11 +1023,17 @@\n \twhile (current) {\n-\t\tsmart_str_appendc(&buf, ':');\n-\t\t/* Fetch next before serializing, in case serialization triggers mutation */\n-\t\tnext = current->next;\n-\t\tphp_var_serialize(&buf, &current->data, &var_hash);\n-\t\t/* If current was freed during serialization, next is still valid */\n-\t\tcurrent = next;\n+\t\tsmart_str_appendc(&buf, ':');\n+\t\t/* Fetch next and copy data before serializing, in case serialization triggers mutation */\n+\t\tnext = current->next;\n+\t\tzval data_copy;\n+\t\tZVAL_COPY(&data_copy, &current->data);\n+\t\tphp_var_serialize(&buf, &data_copy, &var_hash);\n+\t\tzval_ptr_dtor(&data_copy);\n+\t\t/* If current was freed during serialization, next is still valid */\n+\t\tcurrent = next;\n \t}\n"}`
responded: The previous patch did not resolve the use-after-free, as the sanitizer still reports a read-after-free at the line:
```
php_var_serialize(&buf, &current->data, &var_hash);
```
This means that even after fetching `next = current->next` before serialization, the code still accesses `current->data` after `current` may have been freed by user code during serialization.

**The correct fix is to copy the data to a local variable before calling `php_var_serialize`, so that if the node is freed during serialization, we do not access freed memory.**

Here is the improved patch:

```diff
--- a/ext/spl/spl_dllist.c
+++ b/ext/spl/spl_dllist.c
@@ -1023,11 +1023,17 @@
 	while (current) {
-		smart_str_appendc(&buf, ':');
-		/* Fetch next before serializing, in case serialization triggers mutation */
-		next = current->next;
-		php_var_serialize(&buf, &current->data, &var_hash);
-		/* If current was freed during serialization, next is still valid */
-		current = next;
+		smart_str_appendc(&buf, ':');
+		/* Fetch next and copy data before serializing, in case serialization triggers mutation */
+		next = current->next;
+		zval data_copy;
+		ZVAL_COPY(&data_copy, &current->data);
+		php_var_serialize(&buf, &data_copy, &var_hash);
+		zval_ptr_dtor(&data_copy);
+		/* If current was freed during serialization, next is still valid */
+		current = next;
 	}
```

This way, we never access `current->data` after the user code may have freed `current`.

